{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654636"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18623"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18623"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0,0.88,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78536"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63877"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10236"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26912"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is being examined after a shoulder injury. The patient is standing in the anatomical position. She is asked (in non-medical terms) to abduct her arm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rotation of the arm around its long axis","Movement of the arm forwards in the sagittal plane","Movement of the arm backwards in the sagittal plane","Movement of the arm away from the midline in the coronal plane","Movement of the arm towards the midline in the coronal plane"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of the arm away from the midline in the coronal plane\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes shoulder abduction. This movement occurs in the coronal (frontal) plane and increases the angle between the arm and the trunk of the body. The deltoid and supraspinatus muscles are the primary muscles responsible for this action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of the arm towards the midline in the coronal plane\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes adduction, the opposite of abduction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of the arm forwards in the sagittal plane\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes flexion of the shoulder joint\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of the arm backwards in the sagittal plane\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes extension of the shoulder joint\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotation of the arm around its long axis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes internal or external rotation of the shoulder\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe shoulder joint normally allows approximately 180 degrees of abduction when combined with rotation of the scapula.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abduction moves a limb away from the midline of the body in the coronal plane.","Adduction moves a limb towards the midline of the body in the coronal plane.","The shoulder and hip joints are capable of the greatest range of abduction and adduction movements."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63877"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18623"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63877"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T12:26:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T12:27:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78536"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met